snippet.textDisplay: If you’re going to cook your pizza in a normal oven, my method works pretty well. I prepare the pizza and leave it on a cold pizza pan. I put it into the oven when the oven is still cold, and I put it on the lowest rack. That way when I turn the oven on the element on the bottom is hotter than the rest of the oven and right on the pan. That gives me some good color on the bottom and when the bottom is done the top is just about done too. Sometimes if I want I just put the pizza closer to the top of the oven and then turn the broiler on for a minute to brown the cheese a tad bit more.
snippet.textOriginal: If you’re going to cook your pizza in a normal oven, my method works pretty well. I prepare the pizza and leave it on a cold pizza pan. I put it into the oven when the oven is still cold, and I put it on the lowest rack. That way when I turn the oven on the element on the bottom is hotter than the rest of the oven and right on the pan. That gives me some good color on the bottom and when the bottom is done the top is just about done too. Sometimes if I want I just put the pizza closer to the top of the oven and then turn the broiler on for a minute to brown the cheese a tad bit more.

snippet.textDisplay: Hmm so interesting, I didn't see another method for cast iron that I use. Basically treat it like a pizza stone. Put the iron in over or on the stove to get it super hot. Form your pizza and top it on parchment paper. Once the cast iron is super hot, pull the pizza WITH the parchment paper into the iron, then low broil it on the top rack in the oven for maybe 3-4 mins to your preferred doness!
